The Nigerian equities market ended the second week in the month of February bearish with a decline of 1.11 per cent. The market sustained the losing streak, as bearish sentiment prevailed in three of the five trading sessions of last week, following persistence sell-off on market bellwether stocks. As a result, the All-Share Index (ASI) fell 311.22 points or 1.11 per cent to close at 27,755.87 points. Similarly, investors lost N162 billion as market capitalisation reduced to N14.456 trillion. Performance across sectors was negative for last week. The Consumer Goods index led the losers’ chart by 6.47 per cent due to price declines in Guinness Nigeria, Vitafoam Nigeria and Nestle Nigeria. The Insurance and Oil & Gas indices trailed by a loss of 2.16 per cent and 0.69 per cent on the back of sell-offs in Linkage Assurance, MRS Oil Nigeria and Oando. Similarly, price declines in Wema Bank, Serling Bank and MTN Nigeria dragged the Banking index down by 0.21 per cent. On the flip side, the Industrial Goods index went up by 0.78 per cent owing to price appreciation in Lafarge Africa and BUA Cement.  Market breadth for the week was negative as 19 equities appreciated in price, 35 equities depreciated in price, while 109 equities remained unchanged. Livestock Feeds led the gainers table by 16.67 per cent to close at 70 kobo, per share. United Capital followed with a gain of 15.29 per cent to close at N2.94, while Trans-NationWide Express went up by 11.11 per cent to close to 90 kobo, per share. On the other side, Linkage Assurance led the decliners table by 25.81 per cent to close at 46 kobo, per share. Skyway Aviation Handling Company followed with a loss of 23.26 per cent to close at N2.87 and Guinness Nigeria declined by 16.56 per cent to close at N25.20, per share. Overall, a total turnover of 912.175 million shares worth N12.126 billion in 17,083 deals were traded last week by investors on the floor of the Exchange, in contrast to a total of 1.478 billion shares valued at N20.295 billion that exchanged hands previous week in 23,263 deals.  Outlook for the week In the new week, analysts at Cowry Asset Management Limited expected the NSE ASI to close lower despite the release of generally positive unaudited full 2019 corporate results. Nevertheless, we advise investors to take advantage of the low prices to buy stocks with high dividend yields and trading at cheaper prices. APT Securities and Funds Limited pointed out that the equities market is in its year-end earnings season, it will be advisable to watch out for liquid stocks company release in order to position for dividend yield amongst other returns. 